{
  "version": 2,
  "name": "BlossomField",
  "description": "Scene 2 - the instanced-density scene (scene ladder rung 2, REALTIME_3D P8 instancing at performable scale). A soft rolling terrain (node.grid_mesh 64x64 over 14x14 units -> node.push_mesh displaced by low-frequency node.simplex_field_2d -> node.make_triangles) is object 0 of one node.render_scene. node.scatter_on_mesh samples that same terrain area-weighted and emits Array<InstanceTransform> placements (align_to_normal with vertex-normal-oriented faces, per-instance random scale 0.55..1.35) wired into object 1's instances_1. The instance mesh is REAL SCAN CONTENT: apricot_blossom_cluster_lod.glb - the scan's material-3 cluster decimated offline 321k->80k tris (Blender quadric collapse, one-time; ~240k flat verts, 4x lighter than the raw cluster - the scan's chunks are 65k-vertex budget slices interleaved through the full cluster volume, so any single chunk renders as confetti; the material cluster is the smallest coherent unit, measured 2026-07-11), normalized via gltf_mesh_source fit=unit_box + recenter and textured by its atlas page (gltf_texture_source 3 -> base_color_map_1). Density is therefore SPRIG-count (ceiling 48 ~= 46M verts), not flower-count - thousands-scale density needs a purpose-built low-poly blossom asset (offline mesh surgery, Peter's call), drawn once per placement in the SAME shared-depth pass as the terrain, shadowed by the one warm low sun (the shadow pass instances too, D11). density is THE lead performance card - the static count 1500 is the compile-time buffer ceiling, the card sweeps 0..1500 live and place_main parks unused slots at zero scale so lowering the fader really empties the meadow. flowerScale and camera orbit/tilt/distance round out the surface; modelPath is a file-picker card. Wind on the host terrain (Scene 1's gust machinery driving the surface so rigid instances ride it) is the planned next rung; recenter half-nestles each cluster into the ground - judged acceptable-or-not from renders, no base-anchor fit mode exists yet.",
